The following applies to Linux USB raw printing. That's when in the class co.syscoop.soberano.domain.tracked.PrinterProfile,
the property printMethod is set to PrintMethod.USB_RAW:

1) The name of the printer is configured in a printer profile: 
	Three bars menu (TCPTOOL UI Top-Left) -> Configuration -> Printer profiles
	
2) For an USB printer, that name is the device's identifier. For example: /dev/usb/lp0
	
3) It is desirable to set a printer name only one time during its use time.
	
4) The problem with USB printers in Linux is that, every time the system enumerates USB devices, it assigns numbers 
	in sequence. This can change because: 
	
	a) Different USB Port: Plugging the printer into a different USB port on your computer or a different port on 
		a hub can change its discovery order and thus its number;

.	b) System Reboot: Even with the printer in the same port, a simple reboot can sometimes cause the kernel to 
		discover devices in a different order, changing the assigned number;.

	c) Device Disconnection/Reconnection: Disconnecting and reconnecting the printer might cause it to be rediscovered. 
		If another USB device (like a flash drive) was also connected or disconnected in the meantime, the numbering 
		can shift.
		
	d) Kernel Module Loading: The order in which kernel modules load can be non-deterministic and influence the naming 
		order of devices..

	e) Power State: A printer being turned off or put into a low-power state (like sleep) when other devices are 
		discovered could also affect the numbering order.

	f) Number Persistence: The numbering can "drift." For example, after multiple disconnects and reconnects, a printer 
	might move from lp0 to lp8 without ever being lp1 through lp7.
	
5) To avoid the above, following the following steps:

	5.1) Connect to one of the USB ports, and turn on the USB printer.
	
	5.2) In a terminal, execute this command to find out the device identifier: sudo ls /dev/usb/lp*
	
	5.3) Assuming the identifier is /dev/usb/lp0, find its unique attributes by means of this command:
	
		sudo udevadm info -a -n /dev/usb/lp0 | grep -E 'ATTRS{idVendor}|ATTRS{idProduct}|ATTRS{serial}' | head -3
		
	5.4) Assuming the identifier is /dev/usb/lp0, find the device's path by means of this command:
	
		udevadm info --query=path --name=/dev/usb/lp0
		
	5.5) Now, using the path, find the subsystem the device belongs to by means of this command:
	
		udevadm info --query=property --path=/devices/pci0000:00/0000:00:1a.0/usb1/1-1/1-1.2/1-1.2:1.0/usbmisc/lp0
		
	5.4) Create a new udev rule file. The number at the start (e.g., 99) ensures your rule is processed after many 
		default ones. Command:
		
		sudo nano /etc/udev/rules.d/99-thermal-printer.rules
		
	5.5) Add the following line to the file, replacing the attribute values with the ones you found. 
		The SYMLINK parameter defines the persistent name you want to create.
		
		ACTION=="add", SUBSYSTEM=="usbmisc", KERNEL=="lp*", ATTRS{idVendor}=="28e9", ATTRS{idProduct}=="0289", ATTRS{serial}=="000000000004", SYMLINK+="thermal_printer", MODE="0666"
		
	5.6) Finally, by means of these commands, reload the udev rules and trigger them to create the symlink.
	
		sudo udevadm control --reload-rules
		sudo udevadm trigger
		
	5.7) After this, you should see the new symlink:
	
		ls -l /dev/thermal_printer
		
	5.8) Now, you can use the symlink (/dev/thermal_printer) as the printer profile's printer name field value. In this example:
	
		/dev/thermal_printer
		
		
		
